class Solution {
    public List<String> topKFrequent(String[] words, int k) {
        Map<String, Integer> freq = new HashMap<>();
        for (String w : words) freq.merge(w, 1, Integer::sum);

        PriorityQueue<Map.Entry<String, Integer>> pq =
            new PriorityQueue<>((a, b) -> {
                int cmp = Integer.compare(b.getValue(), a.getValue());
                return cmp != 0 ? cmp : a.getKey().compareTo(b.getKey());
            });

        for (Map.Entry<String, Integer> e : freq.entrySet()) pq.offer(e);

        List<String> res = new ArrayList<>();
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) res.add(pq.poll().getKey());
        return res;
    }
}
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n log k)
space complexity: O(n)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Count frequencies in O(n), then use a min-heap of size k to keep the k most frequent words ordered by frequency descending and lexicographical ascending. Each insertion is O(log k) for n unique words, yielding O(n log k) total.

